Schedule VI: Regulated Bio-Chemicals, Additives, and Dietary Stimulants
This schedule establishes the baseline classification for non-medicinal, legally permissible chemical substances within the habitat. All citizens have a right to consume these items provided they meet the age thresholds established for ecosystem resource conservation and developmental safety.

Category Alpha: Restricted Below Age 6 (Legal Age: 6+)
Substances containing high concentrations of plant hormones, intense synthetic compounds, or heavy neurological excitants that are prohibited for infants and toddlers due to developmental risks.

Soy Protein Isolates & Concentrated Phytoestrogens: Regulated in early childhood diets due to high concentrations of plant-based estrogens impacting early endocrine development.

Synthetic Intense Sweeteners (Aspartame & Sucralose): Permitted as sugar alternatives for adults, but strictly prohibited in infant/toddler rations to protect developing metabolic pathways.

Monosodium Glutamate (MSG): Allowed as a flavor enhancer in standard rations, but restricted from early childhood nutrition blocks to prevent early taste-bud desensitization and neurological over-stimulation.

Highly Refined Fructose Concentrates: Concentrated corn or carbohydrate syrups used for preservation and caloric density, restricted under age 6 to prevent early-onset metabolic stress.

Note:
Soy Proteins & Plant Estrogens (Soy Isolates)
In Plain English: Tofu, soy milk, and heavy soy-based meat alternatives.
Why the rule exists: Soy contains high levels of phytoestrogens (plant hormones). In tiny infants, too much soy can disrupt early endocrine and hormonal development.

Artificial Sweeteners (Aspartame & Sucralose)

In Plain English: Diet sugars (like Splenda, Equal, or zero-calorie sodas).
Why the rule exists: Great for adults trying to avoid sugar, but bad for toddlers. It can confuse a young child's developing metabolism and gut bacteria.

MSG (Monosodium Glutamate)

In Plain English: The ultimate savory flavor booster found in snacks, chips, and broth.
Why the rule exists: MSG is totally safe, but it over-stimulates a toddler’s taste buds. Banning it under age 6 prevents toddlers from rejecting normal, healthy rations in favor of highly addictive savory snacks.

High-Fructose Corn Syrup & Heavy Sugars

In Plain English: Super-concentrated liquid sugars used to sweeten and preserve food.
Why the rule exists: It puts massive metabolic stress on a baby's liver and kidneys, causing early-onset health issues the colony can't afford to treat.



Category Beta: Restricted Below Age 14 (Legal Age: 14+)
Mild central nervous system stimulants and low-attenuation fermented beverages, permitted only after the baseline of structural childhood brain development is reached.

Free Caffeine (Synthetic & Natural Extracts): Isolated caffeine anhydrous, coffee beans, tea concentrates, and caffeine-infused carbonated beverages.

Low-Attenuation Ethanol (ABV under 5.0%): Weakly fermented synthetic mash, light beers, ciders, and hydration-adjacent alcoholic beverages.

Taurine & Glucuronolactone: Common synthetic amino acid derivatives and metabolic agents used in energy synthesis and physical labor endurance blends.

Theobromine & Cacao Concentrates: Primary nervous system stimulants derived from natural cocoa or synthetic equivalents, restricted in high-potency doses.

Guarana & Ginseng Botanical Extracts: Secondary organic stimulants utilized to enhance cognitive focus and delay fatigue during educational cycles.

Standard Caffeine (Natural & Synthetic)
In Plain English: Coffee, standard tea, energy drinks, and caffeinated sodas.
Why the rule exists: It keeps adults awake on night shifts, but jacks up a child’s heart rate, causes severe anxiety, and ruins the strict sleep schedules required in a shared habitat.

Light Alcohol (Under 5% ABV)

In Plain English: Weak beer, hard ciders, and light pre-mixed drinks.
Why the rule exists: This is the colony's compromise. At 14, you can legally have a light beer with dinner or at a community festival, but you aren't allowed near the heavy liquor locker.

Taurine & Energy Drink Additives

In Plain English: The extra chemical boosters packed into energy drinks and pre-workout supplements.
Why the rule exists: These are heavy physical stamina boosters meant for grueling labor shifts, not for hyperactive teenagers.

Theobromine (Pure Cocoa Extracts)

In Plain English: The chemical that gives you a "buzz" or happy feeling when eating deep dark chocolate.
Why the rule exists: While standard chocolate bars are fine, concentrated, pure chemical theobromine acts like a mild amphetamine and is restricted to teens and adults.

Category Gamma: Restricted Below Age 20 (Legal Age: 20+)
High-potency recreational substances and chemical relaxants restricted to fully matured adult physiology to prevent structural habitat disruptions.

High-Attenuation Ethanol (ABV 5.0% and Greater): Standard and fortified wines, heavy beers, and all forms of distilled spirits or pure food-grade ethanol.

Concentrated Phytochemical Sedatives: High-potency, naturally derived relaxants (such as highly concentrated Valerian Root extracts or legal non-medicinal herbal depressants approved by both terrestrial blocs) used for off-shift stress management.

Hard Alcohol (5% ABV and Greater)

In Plain English: Wine, heavy beers, vodka, whiskey, and all standard liquors.
Why the rule exists: To prevent teenage rowdiness, liver damage, and alcohol poisoning. In a closed space station, a drunk teenager can accidentally break life-support infrastructure or cause a riot.

Herbal "Chill Pills" & Downers (Concentrated Valerian Root)

In Plain English: High-strength, legal herbal sedatives used to help people sleep or calm down.
Why the rule exists: These are powerful, non-chemical relaxants used for off-shift stress management. Because they heavily slow down reaction times and brain activity, they are strictly reserved for fully grown adults.
